
# document-builder
Builds a static html page from multiple sources

## How
Download code. Open terminal at project location. Install dependencies `npm install`. Create folders in docs, or modify example contents. This is where you put your partial html or markdown files. Names of the document sections is derived from file- and folder names.


## Custom styles and scripts
Put js and css files in "scripts" and "styles" respectively to have them included inline in the output document.

## Syntax highlight
The project comes preconfigured with prismjs for c#, asp.net, javascript, css and markup. Add code blocks wrapped in applicable tags to partial html files to have them output highlighted.
```
<pre class="language-aspnet"><code>
```

## Assets (adding images)
Put image files into `assets` folder and link them relative to *root project path*, like so: `<img src="assets/my-image.png" />` Supported formats are .jpg, .gif, .png. Files are encoded into base64 and inserted inline.

  ##1-1. Service Installation
  <ol>
<li>Open command prompt (as administrator)</li>
<li>type: cd &quot;C:\Windows\Microsoft.NET\Framework64\v4.0.30319&quot; and press enter</li>
<li>Type: installutil &quot;C:\actionframework\agents\33333\ActionFramework.Agent.exe&quot; and press enter. Results should look like the image below.</li>

#2. Actions


  ##2-1. Create an Action
  <p>Create an action class that inherits from ActionBase.</p>
<pre class="language-csharp"><code>
using ActionFramework.Base;
using System;

namespace DemoApp
{
    public class DemoAction1 : ActionBase
    {
        //define the runtime configuration properties
        public string MyProp { get; set; }

        //override the runtime &amp;quot;execute&amp;quot; function
        public override object Execute()
        {
            try
            {
                //implement action logic, log my &amp;quot;MyProp&amp;quot; value
                Log.Info(&amp;quot;Just make a log entry: &amp;quot; + MyProp);

                return HandleSuccess();
            }
            catch (Exception ex)
            {
                return HandleException(ex);
            }
        }
    }
}
</code>
</pre>

  ##2-2. On Demand (REST) Actions
  <p>Build the Action class.</p>
<pre class="language-csharp">
<code>
public class OnDemandDemo : ActionBase
{
    //GET (no parameters)
        public override object Execute()
        {
            try
            {
                XDocument result = XDocument.Parse(&amp;quot;&lt;xml&gt;content&lt;/xml&gt;&amp;quot;);

                Log.Info(&amp;quot;Parsed filecontent successfully&amp;quot;);

                return result;
            }
            catch (Exception ex)
            {
                return HandleException(ex);
            }
        }

        //POST (object input parameter)
        public override object Execute(object input)
        {
            try
            {
                Log.Info(&amp;quot;Object Input: &amp;quot; + input.ToString());

                return input;
            }
            catch (Exception ex)
            {
                return HandleException(ex);
            }
        }
}
</code>
</pre>

<p>Call the agent API endpoints (GET/POST).</p>
<pre class="language-csharp">
<code>
string uri = &amp;quot;http://localhost:1011/&amp;quot;;

//GET:
var getclient = new RestClient(uri);
var getrequest = new RestRequest(&amp;quot;api/agent/runaction/ondemanddemo&amp;quot;, Method.GET);
var getresponse = getclient.Execute(getrequest);
Console.WriteLine(getresponse.Content);
Console.ReadLine();

//POST:
var postclient = new RestClient(uri);
var postrequest = new RestRequest(&amp;quot;api/agent/runaction?name=ondemanddemo&amp;quot;, Method.POST);
postrequest.RequestFormat = DataFormat.Json;
postrequest.AddBody(new TestModel()
{
    Id = 1,
    Name = &amp;quot;Test&amp;quot;
});

var postresponse = postclient.Execute(postrequest);
Console.WriteLine(postresponse.Content);
Console.ReadLine();
</code>
</pre>

#3. Logging


  ##3-1. Create custom log class
  <p>Create a class that inherits from <strong>ILogElement</strong></p>
<pre class="language-csharp">
<code>
using ActionFramework.Logging;
using System;

namespace DemoApp
{
    internal sealed class CustomLog : ILogElement
    {
        private int amount = 0;
        private DateTime date = DateTime.Now;

        public int Amount
        {
            get { return amount; }
        }

        public DateTime Date
        {
            get { return date; }
            set { date = value; }
        }

        public string Message { get; set; }

        /// &lt;summary&gt;
        /// increase count by 1
        /// &lt;/summary&gt;
        public void Count()
        {
            amount++;
        }

        /// &lt;summary&gt;
        /// increase count by n
        /// &lt;/summary&gt;
        public void Count(int n)
        {
            amount += n;
        }
    }
}
</code>
</pre>

<p>Use the custom logging class in an action class.</p>
<pre class="language-csharp">
<code>
//create the custom log and add values
var log = new CustomLog()
{
    Date = DateTime.Now,
    Message = &amp;quot;This is the custom message&amp;quot;
};

//add a count
log.Count(25);

//create the log
Log.Custom(log);
</code>
</pre>

<p>Log output (XML).</p>
<pre class="language-markup">
<code>
&lt;customlog&gt;
    &lt;amount&gt;25&lt;/amount&gt;
    &lt;date&gt;2015-12-02T13:58:28.9374725Z&lt;/date&gt;
    &lt;message&gt;This is the custom message&lt;/message&gt;
&lt;/customlog&gt;
</code>
</pre>

#3. Logging


  ##3-1. Create custom log class
  <p>Create a class that inherits from <strong>ILogElement</strong></p>
<pre class="language-csharp">
<code>
using ActionFramework.Logging;
using System;

namespace DemoApp
{
    internal sealed class CustomLog : ILogElement
    {
        private int amount = 0;
        private DateTime date = DateTime.Now;

        public int Amount
        {
            get { return amount; }
        }

        public DateTime Date
        {
            get { return date; }
            set { date = value; }
        }

        public string Message { get; set; }

        /// &lt;summary&gt;
        /// increase count by 1
        /// &lt;/summary&gt;
        public void Count()
        {
            amount++;
        }

        /// &lt;summary&gt;
        /// increase count by n
        /// &lt;/summary&gt;
        public void Count(int n)
        {
            amount += n;
        }
    }
}
</code>
</pre>

<p>Use the custom logging class in an action class.</p>
<pre class="language-csharp">
<code>
//create the custom log and add values
var log = new CustomLog()
{
    Date = DateTime.Now,
    Message = &amp;quot;This is the custom message&amp;quot;
};

//add a count
log.Count(25);

//create the log
Log.Custom(log);
</code>
</pre>

<p>Log output (XML).</p>
<pre class="language-markup">
<code>
&lt;customlog&gt;
    &lt;amount&gt;25&lt;/amount&gt;
    &lt;date&gt;2015-12-02T13:58:28.9374725Z&lt;/date&gt;
    &lt;message&gt;This is the custom message&lt;/message&gt;
&lt;/customlog&gt;
</code>
</pre>

#5. How to update documentation


  ##Document builder
  <h2 id="how-to-use-the-documentation-tool">How to use the documentation tool</h2>
<p>Download code. Open terminal at project location. Install dependencies <code>npm install</code>. Create folders in docs, or modify example contents. This is where you put your partial html or markdown files. Names of the document sections is derived from file- and folder names.</p>
<h2 id="custom-styles-and-scripts">Custom styles and scripts</h2>
<p>Put js and css files in &quot;scripts&quot; and &quot;styles&quot; respectively to have them included inline in the output document.</p>
<h2 id="syntax-highlight">Syntax highlight</h2>
<p>The project comes preconfigured with prismjs for c#, asp.net, javascript, css and markup. Add code blocks wrapped in applicable tags to partial html files to have them output highlighted.</p>
<pre><code>&amp;lt;pre class=&amp;quot;language-aspnet&amp;quot;&amp;gt;&amp;lt;code&amp;gt;
</code></pre><h2 id="assets-adding-images-">Assets (adding images)</h2>
<p>Put image files into <code>assets</code> folder and link them relative to <em>root project path</em>, like so: <code>&amp;lt;img src=&amp;quot;assets/my-image.png&amp;quot; /&amp;gt;</code> Supported formats are .jpg, .gif, .png. Files are encoded into base64 and inserted inline.</p>
